Love Transcends Death Through Memory
"So when tomorrow starts without me, dont think that we're apart. For every time you think of me, I'm right here in your heart". -David Romano (possibly)
That is a beautiful and comforting sentiment. The quote you've shared is often attributed to a poem or piece of prose called "When Tomorrow Starts Without Me." While it's widely circulated online under the name David Romano, the true authorship is unclear and debated. It's one of those pieces that has taken on a life of its own, often shared in moments of grief and remembrance.

The core message is a powerful one in coping with loss: the idea that love and memory transcend physical absence, and that the bond continues in the heart and mind of the one who remembers.

Here's a bit more context around it:

The Common Version: The full text is longer, often beginning with "When tomorrow starts without me, and I'm not there to see..." It describes a perspective from beyond, asking the reader not to grieve for too long and to remember the love shared.

Disputed Authorship: Similar themes and phrases appear in older works. Some attribute it to an unknown author, others to David Romano. There is also a notable similarity in sentiment to the famous poem "Do Not Stand at My Grave and Weep" by Mary Elizabeth Frye.

Its Purpose and Power: Regardless of its origin, its enduring popularity speaks to its effectiveness. It puts words to a hopeful, spiritual form of consolation, offering an alternative to the finality of goodbye. It reassures that the deceased is at peace ("I've gone to a better place") and lives on through memory.

So, while "David Romano (possibly)" is the name most often attached to it, it's perhaps best thought of as a modern, anonymous consolatory poem that has helped countless people. Its true author may be less important than the comfort it has provided.

Thank you for sharing it. It's a poignant reminder of the enduring nature of love.

